### Rules of Hooks

React enforces two fundamental rules for hooks to ensure state consistency across renders. Violating them leads to bugs that are hard to debug.

---

### Rule 1: Only Call Hooks at the Top Level

Do not call hooks inside conditions, loops, or nested functions:

```jsx
// Bad - conditional hook
function Bad({ flag }) {
  if (flag) {
    const [data, setData] = useState(null); // Violation
  }
}

// Good - moved to top level
function Good({ flag }) {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);
  // Use data conditionally
}
```

### Rule 2: Only Call Hooks from React Functions

Call hooks from React function components or custom hooks, never from regular JavaScript functions:

```jsx
// Bad - regular function
function getState() {
  const [state, setState] = useState(0); // Violation
}

// Good - custom hook
function useCustomState() {
  const [state, setState] = useState(0);
  return [state, setState];
}
```

### Why These Rules?

| Rule | Reason |
|------|--------|
| Top level only | React relies on call order to maintain state across renders |
| React functions only | Hooks need access to the component's React internals |

### ESLint Plugin

Install `eslint-plugin-react-hooks` to catch violations automatically:

```bash
npm install eslint-plugin-react-hooks --save-dev
```

### Common Violations

```jsx
// Loops - wrong
for (const item of items) {
  useEffect(() => {}); // Violation
}

// Early returns - wrong
function Component() {
  if (something) return null;
  const [state, setState] = useState(); // Violation
}
```

> **Key Point:** The order of hook calls must be identical between renders. Conditions and loops break this order, causing state corruption. Always use the ESLint plugin.

codeExample:
// Correct usage
function Search({ items }) {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState(''); // Top level
  const results = useMemo(               // Top level
    () => items.filter(i => i.includes(query)),
    [items, query]
  );
  return <input value={query} onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)} />;
}
